Since the EKS API is private, the new joiner must be inside the VPC where the cluster is deployed.
-------------------------------------------------------------------

‚úÖ Step 1: Create an IAM User (AWS Console or AWS CLI)
If the new joiner does not already have an IAM user, the administrator creates one.

üëâ Using AWS Console:

Go to AWS IAM ‚Üí Users ‚Üí Add User
Set User Name (e.g., new-joiner)
Select Programmatic Access
Attach AmazonEKSClusterPolicy
Save the Access Key ID and Secret Access Key
üëâ Using AWS CLI:


aws iam create-user --user-name new-joiner
aws iam attach-user-policy --user-name new-joiner --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonEKSClusterPolicy
‚úÖ At this point, the user can authenticate with AWS CLI but does NOT have EKS access yet.

‚úÖ Step 2: Grant EKS Access (AWS Console or EKS Cluster Terminal)
By default, IAM users are NOT allowed to access the EKS cluster. The administrator must explicitly grant access.





‚úÖ Step 4: Configure kubectl for the New Joiner
The new joiner must configure their local machine to access EKS.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Install AWS CLI and kubectl (if not already installed).
2Ô∏è‚É£ Configure AWS CLI with the user's credentials:


aws configure
3Ô∏è‚É£ Update the kubeconfig for the new user:



aws eks update-kubeconfig --region us-east-1 --name my-cluster --role-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/new-joiner
4Ô∏è‚É£ Verify access to the cluster:




kubectl get nodes
‚úÖ If successful, the new joiner can now interact with the EKS cluster.


create ca.crt and ca.key
crte user 
add this user in kube config file 
then crete role and bind


‚úÖ Step 5: Restrict Access with RBAC (Optional)
If you don‚Äôt want to give full access (system:masters), create a RoleBinding:



apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: dev-access
  namespace: dev
subjects:
  - kind: User
    name: new-joiner
    apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: view
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
sh
Copy
Edit
kubectl apply -f rolebinding.yaml
‚úÖ This gives the new joiner "view" access to the dev namespace only.





































